subscribe() sets the list of topics to subscribe and starts the join process in the background, not only is it asynchronous but you may receive any number of assignments during the lifetime of a consumer after the initial call to subscribe().
So you can't make any timing or assignment assumptions following subscribe(), you need to wait for the rebalance (either conciouscly using an on_assign callback or not (just wait for messages)) before you have any idea what partitions or offsets you will consume.

I don't know what you are trying to achieve, but with the above in mind I would restructure your program as so:
```
def assignment(consumer, partitions):
   print('Assignment:', partitions)
  # do something important

def test_consume():
   ...
   c.subscribe( [ topic ], on_assign=)    
   while running:
      msg = c.poll(timeout=1.0)
      if msg is None:
          continue # timeout
      else if msg.error():
           print(msg.error())  #or handle it
       else:
          handle_msg(msg)
```

